The major result of Zwerger and MÃ¼llerâs investigation was that the signal type of the emitted gravitational waveform in their runs was determined by the stiffness of the equation of state of the collapsing core (i.e., the value of Îr). In their simulations, Type I signals (as labelled by MÃ¶nchmeyer et al. [201]) were produced by models with relatively soft equations of state, Îr â² 1.31. Type II signals were produced by the models with stiffer equations of state, Îr â³ 1.32. They found a smooth transition between these signal types if Îr was increased while all other parameters were held fixed. They also observed another class of signal, Type III, for their models with the lowest Îr (= 1.28). Type III waveforms have a large positive peak just prior to bounce, a smaller negative peak just after bounce, and smaller subsequent oscillations with very short periods (see Figure 12). Type III signals were not observed in the evolution of strongly differentially-rotating Îr = 1.28 models and were also not seen in subsequent investigations [168, 230]. Their waveforms were computed with the same technique as used in [201].
